<problem id="fs-id1166167425806">
<para id="fs-id1166167425808">A portion of a long, cylindrical <term class="no-emphasis">coaxial cable</term> is shown in the accompanying figure. A current <emphasis effect="italics">I</emphasis> flows down the center conductor, and this current is returned in the outer conductor. Determine the magnetic field in the regions (a) <m:math><m:mrow><m:mi>r</m:mi><m:mo>≤</m:mo><m:msub><m:mi>r</m:mi><m:mn>1</m:mn></m:msub><m:mo>,</m:mo></m:mrow></m:math> (b) <m:math><m:mrow><m:msub><m:mi>r</m:mi><m:mn>2</m:mn></m:msub><m:mo>≥</m:mo><m:mi>r</m:mi><m:mo>≥</m:mo><m:msub><m:mi>r</m:mi><m:mn>1</m:mn></m:msub><m:mo>,</m:mo></m:mrow></m:math> (c) <m:math><m:mrow><m:msub><m:mi>r</m:mi><m:mn>3</m:mn></m:msub><m:mo>≥</m:mo><m:mi>r</m:mi><m:mo>≥</m:mo><m:msub><m:mi>r</m:mi><m:mn>2</m:mn></m:msub><m:mo>,</m:mo></m:mrow></m:math> and (d) <m:math><m:mrow><m:mi>r</m:mi><m:mo>≥</m:mo><m:msub><m:mi>r</m:mi><m:mn>3</m:mn></m:msub><m:mo>.</m:mo></m:mrow></m:math> Assume that the current is distributed uniformly over the cross sections of the two parts of the cable.</para>
